# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: css-paint-api
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics are mainly used in applications that were originally developed upon traditional printing and drawing technologies, such as typography, cartography, technical drawing, advertising, etc.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] In many domains, such as desktop publishing, engineering, and business, a description of a document based on 2D computer graphics techniques can be much smaller than the corresponding digital image—often by a factor of 1/1000 or more.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] This representation is also more flexible since it can be rendered at different resolutions to suit different output devices.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] For these reasons, documents and illustrations are often stored or transmitted as 2D graphic files.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics started in the 1950s, based on vector graphics devices.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] These were largely supplanted by raster-based devices in the following decades.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] The PostScript language and the X Window System protocol were landmark developments in the field.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics models may combine geometric models (also called vector graphics), digital images (also called raster graphics), text to be typeset (defined by content, font style and size, color, position, and orientation), mathematical functions and equations, and more.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] These components can be modified and manipulated by two-dimensional geometric transformations such as translation, rotation, and scaling.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] In object-oriented graphics, the image is described indirectly by an object endowed with a self-rendering method—a procedure that assigns colors to the image pixels by an arbitrary algorithm.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] Complex models can be built by combining simpler objects, in the paradigms of object-oriented programming.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] In Euclidean geometry, a *translation (geometry)* moves every point a constant distance in a specified direction.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] A translation can be described as a rigid motion: other rigid motions include rotations and reflections.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] A translation can also be interpreted as the addition of a constant vector to every point, or as shifting the origin of the coordinate system.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] If *T* is a translation, then the image of a subset *A* under the function *T* is the **translation** of *A* by *T*.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] The translation of *A* by *T***v** is often written *A* + **v**.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] In a Euclidean space, any translation is an isometry.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] The set of all translations forms the translation group *T*, which is isomorphic to the space itself, and a normal subgroup of Euclidean group *E*(*n* ).
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] Since a translation is an affine transformation but not a linear transformation, homogeneous coordinates are normally used to represent the translation operator by a matrix and thus to make it linear.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] Because addition of vectors is commutative, multiplication of translation matrices is therefore also commutative (unlike multiplication of arbitrary matrices).
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] In linear algebra, a *rotation matrix* is a matrix that is used to perform a rotation in Euclidean space.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] rotates points in the *xy*-Cartesian plane counterclockwise through an angle *θ* about the origin of the Cartesian coordinate system.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] To perform the rotation using a rotation matrix *R*, the position of each point must be represented by a column vector **v**, containing the coordinates of the point.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] A rotated vector is obtained by using the matrix multiplication *R***v**.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] Since matrix multiplication has no effect on the zero vector (i.e., on the coordinates of the origin), rotation matrices can only be used to describe rotations about the origin of the coordinate system.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] Rotation matrices provide a simple algebraic description of such rotations, and are used extensively for computations in geometry, physics, and computer graphics.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] In 2-dimensional space, a rotation can be simply described by an angle *θ* of rotation, but it can be also represented by the 4 entries of a rotation matrix with 2 rows and 2 columns.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] In 3-dimensional space, every rotation can be interpreted as a rotation by a given angle about a single fixed axis of rotation (see Euler's rotation theorem), and hence it can be simply described by an angle and a vector with 3 entries.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] However, it can also be represented by the 9 entries of a rotation matrix with 3 rows and 3 columns.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] The notion of rotation is not commonly used in dimensions higher than 3; there is a notion of a *rotational displacement*, which can be represented by a matrix, but no associated single axis or angle.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] Rotation matrices are square matrices, with real entries.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] The set of all such matrices of size *n* forms a group, known as the special orthogonal group SO(*n*).
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] A convenient way to create a complex image is to start with a blank "canvas" raster map (an array of pixels, also known as a bitmap) filled with some uniform background color and then "draw", "paint" or "paste" simple patches of color onto it, in an appropriate order.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] In particular the canvas may be the frame buffer for a computer display.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] Text, shapes and lines are rendered with a client-specified color.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] Many libraries and cards provide color gradients, which are handy for the generation of smoothly-varying backgrounds, shadow effects, etc.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] The pixel colors can also be taken from a texture, e.g. a digital image (thus emulating rub-on screentones and the fabled *checker paint* which used to be available only in cartoons).
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] Painting a pixel with a given color usually replaces its previous color.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] However, many systems support painting with transparent and translucent colors, which only modify the previous pixel values.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] The two colors may also be combined in more complex ways, e.g. by computing their bitwise exclusive or.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] This technique is known as *inverting color* or *color inversion*, and is often used in graphical user interfaces for highlighting, rubber-band drawing, and other volatile painting—since re-painting the same shapes with the same color will restore the original pixel values.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] The models used in 2D computer graphics usually do not provide for three-dimensional shapes, or three-dimensional optical phenomena such as lighting, shadows, reflection, refraction, etc.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] However, they usually can model multiple *layers* (conceptually of ink, paper, or film; opaque, translucent, or transparent—stacked in a specific order.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] The ordering is usually defined by a single number (the layer's *depth*, or distance from the viewer).
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models are sometimes called "21⁄2-D computer graphics".
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] They make it possible to mimic traditional drafting and printing techniques based on film and paper, such as cutting and pasting; and allow the user to edit any layer without affecting the others.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] For these reasons, they are used in most graphics editors.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models also allow better spatial anti-aliasing of complex drawings and provide a sound model for certain techniques such as *mitered joints* and the even–odd rule.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models are also used to allow the user to suppress unwanted information when viewing or printing a document, e.g. roads or railways from a map, certain process layers from an integrated circuit diagram, or hand annotations from a business letter.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] In a layer-based model, the target image is produced by "painting" or "pasting" each layer, in order of decreasing depth, on the virtual canvas.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] Conceptually, each layer is first rendered on its own, yielding a digital image with the desired resolution which is then painted over the canvas, pixel by pixel.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] Fully transparent parts of a layer need not be rendered, of course.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] The rendering and painting may be done in parallel, i.e., each layer pixel may be painted on the canvas as soon as it is produced by the rendering procedure.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] Layers that consist of complex geometric objects (such as text or polylines) may be broken down into simpler elements (characters or line segments, respectively), which are then painted as separate layers, in some order.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] However, this solution may create undesirable aliasing artifacts wherever two elements overlap the same pixel.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] See also Portable Document Format#Layers.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] Modern computer graphics card displays almost overwhelmingly use raster techniques, dividing the screen into a rectangular grid of pixels, due to the relatively low cost of raster-based video hardware as compared with vector graphic hardware.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] Most graphic hardware has internal support for blitting operations or sprite drawing.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] A co-processor dedicated to blitting is known as a *Blitter chip*.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] Many graphical user interfaces (GUIs), including macOS, Microsoft Windows, or the X Window System, are primarily based on 2D graphical concepts.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] Such software provides a visual environment for interacting with the computer, and commonly includes some form of window manager to aid the user in conceptually distinguishing between different applications.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] The user interface within individual software applications is typically 2D in nature as well, due in part to the fact that most common input devices, such as the mouse, are constrained to two dimensions of movement.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics are very important in the control peripherals such as printers, plotters, sheet cutting machines, etc.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] They were also used in most early video games; and are still used for card and board games such as solitaire, chess, mahjongg, etc.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics editors or *drawing programs* are application-level software for the creation of images, diagrams and illustrations by direct manipulation (through the mouse, graphics tablet, or similar device) of 2D computer graphics primitives.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] These editors generally provide geometric primitives as well as digital images; and some even support procedural models.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] The illustration is usually represented internally as a layered model, often with a hierarchical structure to make editing more convenient.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] These editors generally output graphics files where the layers and primitives are separately preserved in their original form.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] MacDraw, introduced in 1984 with the Macintosh line of computers, was an early example of this class; recent examples are the commercial products Adobe Illustrator and CorelDRAW, and the free editors such as xfig or Inkscape.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] There are also many 2D graphics editors specialized for certain types of drawings such as electrical, electronic and VLSI diagrams, topographic maps, computer fonts, etc.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] Image editors are specialized for the manipulation of digital images, mainly by means of free-hand drawing/painting and signal processing operations.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] They typically use a direct-painting paradigm, where the user controls virtual pens, brushes, and other free-hand artistic instruments to apply paint to a virtual canvas.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] Some image editors support a multiple-layer model; however, in order to support signal-processing operations like blurring each layer is normally represented as a digital image.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] Therefore, any geometric primitives that are provided by the editor are immediately converted to pixels and painted onto the canvas.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] The name *raster graphics editor* is sometimes used to contrast this approach to that of general editors which also handle *vector graphics*.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] One of the first popular image editors was Apple's MacPaint, companion to MacDraw.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] Modern examples are the free GIMP editor, and the commercial products Photoshop and Paint Shop Pro.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] This class too includes many specialized editors—for medicine, remote sensing, digital photography, etc.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] With the resurgence of 2D animation, free and proprietary software packages have become widely available for amateurs and professional animators.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] With software like RETAS UbiArt Framework and Adobe After Effects, coloring and compositing can be done in less time.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] Various approaches have been developed to aid and speed up the process of digital 2D animation.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] For example, by generating vector artwork in a tool like Adobe Flash an artist may employ software-driven automatic coloring and in-betweening.
[src:css-paint-api/2d-computer-graphics] Programs like Blender or Adobe Substance allow the user to do either 3D animation, 2D animation or combine both in its software allowing experimentation with multiple forms of animation.
[src:css-paint-api/css-paint] This feature is not Baseline because it does not work in some of the most widely-used browsers.
[src:css-paint-api/css-paint] The **`paint()`** CSS function defines an `<image>` value generated with a PaintWorklet.
[src:css-paint-api/css-paint] In the CSS, we define the `background-image` as a `paint()` type with the worklet name, `boxbg`, along with any variables (ex.
[src:css-paint-api/css-paint] You can pass optional arguments in the CSS `paint()` function.
[src:css-paint-api/css-paint] We've included a custom property in the selector block defining a boxColor.
[src:css-paint-api/css-paint] Custom properties are accessible to the PaintWorklet.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] The CSS Paint API is designed to enable developers to programmatically define images which can then be used anywhere a CSS image can be invoked, such as CSS `background-image`, `border-image`, `mask-image`, etc.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] In an external script file, we employ the `registerPaint()` function to name our CSS Paint worklet.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] The first is the name we give the worklet — this is the name we will use in our CSS as the parameter of the `paint()` function when we want to apply this styling to an element.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] The second parameter is the class that does all the magic, defining the context options and what to paint to the two-dimensional canvas that will be our image.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] In this class example we have defined a single context option with the `contextOptions()` function: we returned an object stating alpha transparency is allowed.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] We have then used the `paint()` function to paint to our canvas.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] A `paint()` function can take three arguments.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] Here we have provided one argument: the rendering context (we'll look at more in due course), often referred to by the variable name `ctx`.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] We define the `fillStyle` as being `hsl(55 90% 60% / 100%)`, which is a shade of yellow, and then call `fillRect()` to create a rectangle of that color.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] The `fillRect()` parameters are, in order, x-axis origin, y-axis origin, width, and height.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] `fillRect(0, 15, 200, 20)` results in the creation of a rectangle that is 200 units wide by 20 units tall, positioned 0 units from the left and 15 units from the top of the content box.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] We can use the CSS `background-size` and `background-position` properties to re-size or relocate this background image, but this is the default size and placement of the yellow box we created in our paint worklet.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] For more options, look at the `<canvas>` documentation.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] We also add a little bit of complexity later in this tutorial.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] The setup and design of our paint worklet took place in the external script shown above.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] We need to register that `worklet` from our main script.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] This can be done using the paint worklet's `addModule()` method in a `<script>` within the main HTML or in an external JavaScript file linked from the document.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] In our example, the paintworklet is stored alongside the main script file.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] Once we have a registered paint worklet, we can use it in CSS.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] Employ the CSS `paint()` function like we would any other `<image>` type, using the same string identifier we used in the paintworklet's `registerPaint()` function.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] The following example will look like the image above in browsers supporting the CSS Painting API.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] While you can't play with the worklet's script, you can alter the `background-size` and `background-position` to change the size and location of the background image.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] In the example above, we created a 20x200 unit box, painted 15 units from the top of the element it is the same regardless of the size of the element.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] If the text is small, the yellow box looks like a huge underline.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] If the text is huge, the box might look like a bar above the first three letters.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] It would be better if the background image was relative to the size of the element — we can use the element's `paintSize` property to ensure the background image is proportional to the size of the element's box model size.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] In the above image, the background is proportional to the size of the element.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] The 3rd example has `width: 50%`; set on the block level element, making the element narrower and therefore the background image narrower.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] We've changed the dimensions and positioning of our rectangle to be relative to the size of the element box rather than absolute values.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] We can pass the second parameter into the `paint()` function to give us access to the width and the height of the element, via `.width` and `.height` properties.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] Our header now has a highlight that changes according to its size.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] While you can't play with the worklet's script, you can alter the element's `font-size` and `width` to change the size of the background image.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] In browsers that support the CSS Paint API, the elements in the example below should get yellow backgrounds proportional to their font size.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] In addition to accessing the size of the element, the worklet can also have access to CSS custom properties and regular CSS properties.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] The three parameters of the `paint()` function include the drawing context, paint size and properties.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] To be able to access properties, we include the static `inputProperties()` method, which provides live access to CSS properties, including regular properties and custom properties, and returns an array of property names.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] We'll take a look at `inputArguments` in the last section.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] Let's create a list of items with a background image that rotates between three different colors and three widths.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] To achieve this we'll define two custom CSS properties, `--box-color` and `--width-subtractor`.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] In our worklet, we can reference these custom properties.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] We used the `inputProperties()` method in the `registerPaint()` class to get the values of two custom properties set on an element that has `boxbg` applied to it and then used those within our `paint()` function.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] The `inputProperties()` method can return all properties affecting the element, not just custom properties.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] In our CSS, we define the `--box-color` and `--width-subtractor` custom properties.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] While you can't play with the worklet's script, you can alter the custom property values in DevTools to change the colors and width of the background image.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] Let's take a look at a more complex paint example.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] While you can't edit the worklet itself, you can play around with the CSS and HTML.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] Maybe try `scale` and `rotate` on the headers?
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] You could try making the background images above without the CSS Paint API.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] It is doable, but you would have to declare a different, fairly complex linear gradient for each different color you wanted to create.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] With the CSS Paint API, one worklet can be reused, with different colors passed in this case.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] With the CSS Paint API, we not only have access to custom properties and regular properties, but we can pass custom arguments to the `paint()` function as well.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] We can add these extra arguments when we call the function in the CSS.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] Let's say we want to sometimes stroke our background instead of fill it — let's pass in an extra argument for this occasion.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] Now we can use the `inputArguments()` method in the `registerPaint()` class to access the custom argument we have added to our `paint()` function.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] We can also specify that we want a particular type of argument.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] When we `get` our list of argument values, we can ask specifically for a `<length>` unit.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] In this case, we specifically requested the `<length>` attribute.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] The first element in the returned array will be a `CSSUnparsedValue`.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] If the custom argument is a CSS value, for instance a unit, we can invoke Typed OM CSSStyleValue class (and sub classes) by using the value type keyword when we retrieve it in the `registerPaint()` function.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] Now we can access the type and value properties, meaning we can get the number of pixels and a number type right out of the box.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] It's worth noting the difference between using custom properties to control different parts of this worklet and the arguments set out here.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] Custom properties (and in fact any properties on the style map) are global — they can be used elsewhere within our CSS (and JS).
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] You may for example have a `--main-color`, which will be useful for setting the color within a `paint()` function, but can also be used to set colors elsewhere in your CSS.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] If you wanted to change it specifically for paint, it could prove difficult.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] This is where the custom argument feature comes in handy.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] Another way to think about it is that arguments are set to control what you are actually drawing, whereas properties are set to control styling.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api-guide] Now we can really start to see the benefits of this API, if we can control a myriad of drawing parameters from our CSS through both custom properties and extra `paint()` function arguments, then we can really start to build reusable and highly controllable styling functions.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api] The CSS Painting API — part of the CSS Houdini umbrella of APIs — allows developers to write JavaScript functions that can draw directly into an element's background, border, or content.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api] Essentially, the CSS Painting API contains functionality allowing developers to create custom values for `paint()`, a CSS `<image>` function.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api] You can then apply these values to properties like `background-image` to set complex custom backgrounds on an element.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api] The API defines a `worklet` that can be used to programmatically generate an image that responds to computed style changes.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api] To find out more about how this is used, consult Using the CSS Painting API.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api] The global execution context of the paint worklet.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api] The rendering context for the CSS Painting API's rendering context for drawing to the bitmap.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api] Represents the size of the output bitmap that the author should draw.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api] The following example creates a list of items with a background image that rotates between three different colors and three widths.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api] In a supporting browser you will see something like the image below.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api] The worklet is an external JavaScript file (in this case we've called it `boxbg.js`) which defines a paint `worklet`.
[src:css-paint-api/css-painting-api] The setup and logic of the paint worklet is in the external script.
[src:css-paint-api/paintworklet] The **`PaintWorkletGlobalScope`** interface of the CSS Painting API represents the global object available inside a paint `Worklet`.
[src:css-paint-api/paintworklet] To avoid leaking visited links, this feature is currently disabled in Chrome-based browsers for `<a>` elements with an `href` attribute, and for children of such elements.
[src:css-paint-api/paintworklet] Returns the current device's ratio of physical pixels to logical pixels.
[src:css-paint-api/paintworklet] Registers a class to programmatically generate an image where a CSS property expects a file.
[src:css-paint-api/paintworklet] The following three examples go together to show creating, loading, and using a paint `Worklet`.
[src:css-paint-api/paintworklet] The following shows an example worklet module.
[src:css-paint-api/paintworklet] Note that `registerPaint()` is called without a reference to a paint `Worklet`.
[src:css-paint-api/paintworklet] The following example demonstrates loading the above worklet from its js file and does so by feature detection.
[src:css-paint-api/paintworklet] This example shows how to use a paint `Worklet` in a stylesheet, including the simplest way to provide a fallback if `CSS.paintWorklet` isn't supported.
[src:css-paint-api/paintworklet] You can also use the `@supports` at-rule.
[src:css-paint-api/rasterisation] In computer graphics, **rasterisation** (British English) or **rasterization** (American English) is the task of taking an image described in a vector graphics format (shapes) and converting it into a raster image which represents the original image.
[src:css-paint-api/rasterisation] The rasterized image may then be displayed on a computer display, video display or printer, or stored in a bitmap file format.
[src:css-paint-api/rasterisation] Rasterization may refer to the technique of drawing 3D models, or to the conversion of 2D rendering primitives, such as polygons and line segments, into a rasterized format.
[src:css-paint-api/rasterisation] The term "rasterisation" comes from German *Raster* 'grid, pattern, schema' and Latin *rāstrum* 'scraper, rake'.
[src:css-paint-api/rasterisation] Bresenham's line algorithm is an example of an algorithm used to rasterize lines.
[src:css-paint-api/rasterisation] Algorithms such as the midpoint circle algorithm are used to render circles onto a pixelated canvas.
[src:css-paint-api/rasterisation] Polygons are a common representation of digital 3D models.
[src:css-paint-api/rasterisation] Before rasterization, individual polygons are triangulated - therefore, a typical problem to solve in 3D rasterization is rasterization of a triangle.
[src:css-paint-api/rasterisation] 2. no pixel is rasterized more than once, i.e. the rasterized triangles don't overlap.
[src:css-paint-api/rasterisation] This is to guarantee that the result doesn't depend on the order in which the triangles are rasterized.
[src:css-paint-api/rasterisation] Overdrawing pixels can also mean wasting computing power on pixels that would be overwritten.
[src:css-paint-api/rasterisation] This leads to establishing **rasterization rules** to guarantee the above conditions.
[src:css-paint-api/rasterisation] 2. its center lies exactly on the triangle edge (or multiple edges in case of corners) – that is (or, in case of corners, all are), either the *top* or *left* edge.
[src:css-paint-api/rasterisation] A *top* edge is an edge that is exactly horizontal and lies above other edges, and a *left* edge is a non-horizontal edge that is on the left side of the triangle.
[src:css-paint-api/rasterisation] This rule decides which triangle a pixel on a boundary belongs to.
[src:css-paint-api/rasterisation] It is implemented by Direct3D and OpenGL (although the specification here only requires a consistent rule).
[src:css-paint-api/rasterisation] Rasterization is one of the typical techniques of rendering 3D models.
[src:css-paint-api/rasterisation] Compared with other rendering techniques such as ray tracing, rasterization is extremely fast and therefore used in most realtime 3D engines.
[src:css-paint-api/rasterisation] However, rasterization is simply the process of computing the mapping from scene geometry to pixels and does not prescribe a particular way to compute the color of those pixels.
[src:css-paint-api/rasterisation] The specific color of each pixel is assigned by a pixel shader (which in modern GPUs is completely programmable).
[src:css-paint-api/rasterisation] Shading may take into account physical effects such as light position, their approximations or purely artistic intent.
[src:css-paint-api/rasterisation] The process of rasterizing 3D models onto a 2D plane for display on a computer screen ("screen space") is often carried out by fixed function (non-programmable) hardware within the graphics pipeline.
[src:css-paint-api/rasterisation] This is because there is no motivation for modifying the techniques for rasterization used at render time and a special-purpose system allows for high efficiency.
[src:css-paint-api/rasterisation] The quality of rasterization can be improved by antialiasing, which creates "smooth" edges.
[src:css-paint-api/rasterisation] Sub-pixel precision is a method which takes into account positions on a finer scale than the pixel grid and can produce different results even if the endpoints of a primitive fall into same pixel coordinates, producing smoother movement animations.
[src:css-paint-api/rasterisation] Simple or older hardware, such as PlayStation 1, lacked sub-pixel precision in 3D rasterization.
